    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-04-08T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-04-08T13:00:00-05:00" n="701"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d701">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/2625: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Heath</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-08T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 8, 1933—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. The Haitian Minister of Finance intends to re-submit to the Legislature the
                    permanent finance law drafted by the Financial Adviser and transmitted to the
                    Department in the Legation’s despatch No. 483 of August 29, 1932.<note n="86"
                        xml:id="d701fn86">Not printed.</note> The Minister, however, proposes to
                    omit the special article 36 which confirms the powers of the Financial Adviser
                    now exercised by virtue of the Treaty of 1915<note n="87" xml:id="d701fn87">
                        <ref target="frus1916#pg_328">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, p. 328</ref>.</note> and
                    existing accords until the “liquidation” of those instruments. He says that it
                    would be impossible to get the Legislature to vote this article but that the
                    Government will confirm these powers in a note to the Legation employing the
                    same language as that of the article in question.</p>
                <p>I recommend that the Financial Adviser be authorized to approve this law upon the
                    condition that the Haitian Government will confirm in writing the powers
                    mentioned in article 36.</p>
                <p>Please instruct by cable since the budget, of which the finance law forms a part,
                    is to be submitted to the Legislature in accordance with the constitution early
                    next week.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Heath</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
